Microsoft Outlook 2000 Welcome to Microsoft Outlook 2000! 2008-07-06 13:08:43 IST 2008-07-06 13:08:43 IST \\Top of Personal Folders\Inbox 2097188 Yes -----HEADERS----- Received: from The Microsoft Outlook Team ---END HEADERS-- Welcome to Microsoft Outlook 2000 One Window to Your World of Information Microsoft(R) Outlook(R) 2000 is the premier messaging and collaboration client that helps you achieve better results by combining the leading support for Internet standards-based and Microsoft Exchange Server-based e-mail with integrated calendar, contact, and task management features. In Outlook, information is organized in folders. When you first start Outlook, the Inbox folder is opened. Use the Inbox to read and send e-mail messages, meeting requests, and task requests. To create a message, click the File menu, point to New, and then click Mail Message. Type recipient names in the To and Cc boxes. Type the subject of the message in the Subject box, and then type the message in the text box. When you are ready to send the message, click Send. To quickly go to another part of Outlook, click a shortcut icon on the Outlook Bar to the left of the Inbox. For example, click Calendar to open your Calendar folder. The Folder Banner (horizontal bar above the information viewer) shows the name of the open folder. To see a complete list of your folders, click the folder name in the Folder Banner. Here are some of the new features in Outlook 2000: Outlook(R) Today gives you a customizable quick overview of your e-mail calendar, and task information in one place. Easily access Outlook Today from the icon in your Outlook Bar or display it as your default view when you start Outlook to quickly prioritize your work. Create a shortcut in the Outlook Bar to any file, folder or Web page. Click on an Outlook Bar shortcut to a Web page to display the related Web page in the right-hand pane of Outlook for frequently used Web sites or pages. Send and receive your e-mail in HTML format to make messages as rich and compelling as content on the Web. Take advantage of Outlook's Internet protocol support for POP3/SMTP, IMAP4, LDAP, NNTP, S/MIME, HTML Mail, vCard, and iCalendar. Use the innovative Find tool to quickly find messages, appointments or tasks using a Web-style search to specify the desired information. Bring order to your life by using the Organize Tool button on the toolbar to easily organize the contents of a folder, set up rules and even filter out junk e-mail. Publish your personal or team calendar as a Web page using a single command. Create and store your personal distribution lists along with your contacts in your Contacts folder. Manage mass mailings with Mail Merge for e-mail, fax or print distribution to selected or all contacts based on any set of contact fields. Use the Activities tab on a contact item to dynamically track and view all activity related to a contact such as e-mail, appointments and tasks. For more information: Be sure to visit Office Update at http://officeupdate.microsoft.com/outlook - it's the one Web site devoted solely to helping you get the most out of Microsoft(R) Outlook(R) 2000. a.. Extend the usefulness of Outlook 2000 with new add-ins, utilities, and other downloads. b.. Make Outlook 2000 even easier to use with time-saving tips and troubleshooting advice. c.. Visit our Outlook 2000 public newsgroups for feedback, frequently asked questions and tips. d.. Learn about special offers and a wide variety of third-party add-on products that extend the functionality of Outlook 2000. e.. Obtain a list of the most frequent Outlook 2000 support questions. f.. Get the latest Outlook 2000 software updates. We hope you enjoy your experience with Microsoft Outlook, the most integrated e-mail program available today! - The Microsoft Outlook Team {\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\fromhtml1 \deff0{\fonttbl Microsoft Outlook 2000 Welcome to Microsoft Outlook 2000! 2008-07-10 13:17:23 IST 2008-07-10 13:17:23 IST \\Top of Personal Folders\Inbox 2097188 Yes -----HEADERS----- Received: from The Microsoft Outlook Team ---END HEADERS-- Welcome to Microsoft Outlook 2000 One Window to Your World of Information Microsoft(R) Outlook(R) 2000 is the premier messaging and collaboration client that helps you achieve better results by combining the leading support for Internet standards-based and Microsoft Exchange Server-based e-mail with integrated calendar, contact, and task management features. In Outlook, information is organized in folders. When you first start Outlook, the Inbox folder is opened. Use the Inbox to read and send e-mail messages, meeting requests, and task requests. To create a message, click the File menu, point to New, and then click Mail Message. Type recipient names in the To and Cc boxes. Type the subject of the message in the Subject box, and then type the message in the text box. When you are ready to send the message, click Send. To quickly go to another part of Outlook, click a shortcut icon on the Outlook Bar to the left of the Inbox. For example, click Calendar to open your Calendar folder. The Folder Banner (horizontal bar above the information viewer) shows the name of the open folder. To see a complete list of your folders, click the folder name in the Folder Banner. Here are some of the new features in Outlook 2000: Outlook(R) Today gives you a customizable quick overview of your e-mail calendar, and task information in one place. Easily access Outlook Today from the icon in your Outlook Bar or display it as your default view when you start Outlook to quickly prioritize your work. Create a shortcut in the Outlook Bar to any file, folder or Web page. Click on an Outlook Bar shortcut to a Web page to display the related Web page in the right-hand pane of Outlook for frequently used Web sites or pages. Send and receive your e-mail in HTML format to make messages as rich and compelling as content on the Web. Take advantage of Outlook's Internet protocol support for POP3/SMTP, IMAP4, LDAP, NNTP, S/MIME, HTML Mail, vCard, and iCalendar. Use the innovative Find tool to quickly find messages, appointments or tasks using a Web-style search to specify the desired information. Bring order to your life by using the Organize Tool button on the toolbar to easily organize the contents of a folder, set up rules and even filter out junk e-mail. Publish your personal or team calendar as a Web page using a single command. Create and store your personal distribution lists along with your contacts in your Contacts folder. Manage mass mailings with Mail Merge for e-mail, fax or print distribution to selected or all contacts based on any set of contact fields. Use the Activities tab on a contact item to dynamically track and view all activity related to a contact such as e-mail, appointments and tasks. For more information: Be sure to visit Office Update at http://officeupdate.microsoft.com/outlook - it's the one Web site devoted solely to helping you get the most out of Microsoft(R) Outlook(R) 2000. a.. Extend the usefulness of Outlook 2000 with new add-ins, utilities, and other downloads. b.. Make Outlook 2000 even easier to use with time-saving tips and troubleshooting advice. c.. Visit our Outlook 2000 public newsgroups for feedback, frequently asked questions and tips. d.. Learn about special offers and a wide variety of third-party add-on products that extend the functionality of Outlook 2000. e.. Obtain a list of the most frequent Outlook 2000 support questions. f.. Get the latest Outlook 2000 software updates. We hope you enjoy your experience with Microsoft Outlook, the most integrated e-mail program available today! - The Microsoft Outlook Team {\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\fromhtml1 \deff0{\fonttbl When {\*\htmltag4 \par } {\*\htmltag84 }you first start Outlook, the Inbox folder is opened. Use the Inbox to read {\*\htmltag4 \par } {\*\htmltag84 }and send e-mail messages, meeting requests, and task requests.\htmlrtf }\htmlrtf0 \htmlrtf\par}\htmlrtf0 \htmlrtf \par \htmlrtf0 {\*\htmltag72 </P>} {\*\htmltag0 \par } {\*\htmltag240 } {\*\htmltag64 <P>}\htmlrtf {\htmlrtf0 \htmlrtf {\htmlrtf0 To create a message, click the File menu, point to New, and then click {\*\htmltag4 \par } {\*\htmltag84 }Mail Message. Type recipient names in the To and Cc boxes. Type the {\*\htmltag4 \par } {\*\htmltag84 }subject of the message in the Subject box, and then type the message in {\*\htmltag4 \par } {\*\htmltag84 }the text box. When you are ready to send the message, click Send.\htmlrtf }\htmlrtf0 \htmlrtf\par}\htmlrtf0 \htmlrtf \par \htmlrtf0 {\*\htmltag72 </P>} {\*\htmltag0 \par } {\*\htmltag240 } {\*\htmltag64 <P>}\htmlrtf {\htmlrtf0 \htmlrtf {\htmlrtf0 To quickly go to another part of Outlook, click a shortcut icon on the {\*\htmltag4 \par } {\*\htmltag84 }Outlook Bar to the left of the Inbox. For example, click Calendar to open {\*\htmltag4 \par } {\*\htmltag84 }your Calendar folder. The Folder Banner (horizontal bar above the {\*\htmltag4 \par } {\*\htmltag84 }information viewer) shows the name of the open folder. To see a complete {\*\htmltag4 \par } {\*\htmltag84 }list of your folders, click the folder name in the Folder {\*\htmltag4 \par } {\*\htmltag84 }Banner.\htmlrtf }\htmlrtf0 \htmlrtf\par}\htmlrtf0 Microsoft Outlook 2000 Welcome to Microsoft Outlook 2000! 2008-07-10 13:17:23 IST 2008-07-10 13:17:23 IST \\Top of Personal Folders\Inbox 2097188 Yes -----HEADERS----- Received: from The Microsoft Outlook Team ---END HEADERS-- Welcome to Microsoft Outlook 2000 One Window to Your World of Information Microsoft(R) Outlook(R) 2000 is the premier messaging and collaboration client that helps you achieve better results by combining the leading support for Internet standards-based and Microsoft Exchange Server-based e-mail with integrated calendar, contact, and task management features. In Outlook, information is organized in folders. When you first start Outlook, the Inbox folder is opened. Use the Inbox to read and send e-mail messages, meeting requests, and task requests. To create a message, click the File menu, point to New, and then click Mail Message. Type recipient names in the To and Cc boxes. Type the subject of the message in the Subject box, and then type the message in the text box. When you are ready to send the message, click Send. To quickly go to another part of Outlook, click a shortcut icon on the Outlook Bar to the left of the Inbox. For example, click Calendar to open your Calendar folder. The Folder Banner (horizontal bar above the information viewer) shows the name of the open folder. To see a complete list of your folders, click the folder name in the Folder Banner. Here are some of the new features in Outlook 2000: Outlook(R) Today gives you a customizable quick overview of your e-mail calendar, and task information in one place. Easily access Outlook Today from the icon in your Outlook Bar or display it as your default view when you start Outlook to quickly prioritize your work. Create a shortcut in the Outlook Bar to any file, folder or Web page. Click on an Outlook Bar shortcut to a Web page to display the related Web page in the right-hand pane of Outlook for frequently used Web sites or pages. Send and receive your e-mail in HTML format to make messages as rich and compelling as content on the Web. Take advantage of Outlook's Internet protocol support for POP3/SMTP, IMAP4, LDAP, NNTP, S/MIME, HTML Mail, vCard, and iCalendar. Use the innovative Find tool to quickly find messages, appointments or tasks using a Web-style search to specify the desired information. Bring order to your life by using the Organize Tool button on the toolbar to easily organize the contents of a folder, set up rules and even filter out junk e-mail. Publish your personal or team calendar as a Web page using a single command. Create and store your personal distribution lists along with your contacts in your Contacts folder. Manage mass mailings with Mail Merge for e-mail, fax or print distribution to selected or all contacts based on any set of contact fields. Use the Activities tab on a contact item to dynamically track and view all activity related to a contact such as e-mail, appointments and tasks. For more information: Be sure to visit Office Update at http://officeupdate.microsoft.com/outlook - it's the one Web site devoted solely to helping you get the most out of Microsoft(R) Outlook(R) 2000. a.. Extend the usefulness of Outlook 2000 with new add-ins, utilities, and other downloads. b.. Make Outlook 2000 even easier to use with time-saving tips and troubleshooting advice. c.. Visit our Outlook 2000 public newsgroups for feedback, frequently asked questions and tips. d.. Learn about special offers and a wide variety of third-party add-on products that extend the functionality of Outlook 2000. e.. Obtain a list of the most frequent Outlook 2000 support questions. f.. Get the latest Outlook 2000 software updates. We hope you enjoy your experience with Microsoft Outlook, the most integrated e-mail program available today! - The Microsoft Outlook Team {\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\fromhtml1 \deff0{\fonttbl Microsoft Outlook 2000 Welcome to Microsoft Outlook 2000! 2008-07-10 13:17:23 IST 2008-07-10 13:17:23 IST \\Top of Personal Folders\Inbox 2097188 Yes -----HEADERS----- Received: from The Microsoft Outlook Team ---END HEADERS-- Welcome to Microsoft Outlook 2000 One Window to Your World of Information Microsoft(R) Outlook(R) 2000 is the premier messaging and collaboration client that helps you achieve better results by combining the leading support for Internet standards-based and Microsoft Exchange Server-based e-mail with integrated calendar, contact, and task management features. In Outlook, information is organized in folders. When you first start Outlook, the Inbox folder is opened. Use the Inbox to read and send e-mail messages, meeting requests, and task requests. To create a message, click the File menu, point to New, and then click Mail Message. Type recipient names in the To and Cc boxes. Type the subject of the message in the Subject box, and then type the message in the text box. When you are ready to send the message, click Send. To quickly go to another part of Outlook, click a shortcut icon on the Outlook Bar to the left of the Inbox. For example, click Calendar to open your Calendar folder. The Folder Banner (horizontal bar above the information viewer) shows the name of the open folder. To see a complete list of your folders, click the folder name in the Folder Banner. Here are some of the new features in Outlook 2000: Outlook(R) Today gives you a customizable quick overview of your e-mail calendar, and task information in one place. Easily access Outlook Today from the icon in your Outlook Bar or display it as your default view when you start Outlook to quickly prioritize your work. Create a shortcut in the Outlook Bar to any file, folder or Web page. Click on an Outlook Bar shortcut to a Web page to display the related Web page in the right-hand pane of Outlook for frequently used Web sites or pages. Send and receive your e-mail in HTML format to make messages as rich and compelling as content on the Web. Take advantage of Outlook's Internet protocol support for POP3/SMTP, IMAP4, LDAP, NNTP, S/MIME, HTML Mail, vCard, and iCalendar. Use the innovative Find tool to quickly find messages, appointments or tasks using a Web-style search to specify the desired information. Bring order to your life by using the Organize Tool button on the toolbar to easily organize the contents of a folder, set up rules and even filter out junk e-mail. Publish your personal or team calendar as a Web page using a single command. Create and store your personal distribution lists along with your contacts in your Contacts folder. Manage mass mailings with Mail Merge for e-mail, fax or print distribution to selected or all contacts based on any set of contact fields. Use the Activities tab on a contact item to dynamically track and view all activity related to a contact such as e-mail, appointments and tasks. For more information: Be sure to visit Office Update at http://officeupdate.microsoft.com/outlook - it's the one Web site devoted solely to helping you get the most out of Microsoft(R) Outlook(R) 2000. a.. Extend the usefulness of Outlook 2000 with new add-ins, utilities, and other downloads. b.. Make Outlook 2000 even easier to use with time-saving tips and troubleshooting advice. c.. Visit our Outlook 2000 public newsgroups for feedback, frequently asked questions and tips. d.. Learn about special offers and a wide variety of third-party add-on products that extend the functionality of Outlook 2000. e.. Obtain a list of the most frequent Outlook 2000 support questions. f.. Get the latest Outlook 2000 software updates. We hope you enjoy your experience with Microsoft Outlook, the most integrated e-mail program available today! - The Microsoft Outlook Team {\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\fromhtml1 \deff0{\fonttbl alison@m57.biz Jean User <jean@m57.biz> This is what I was talking about 2008-07-06 13:25:00 IST 2008-07-06 13:25:00 IST \\Top of Personal Folders\Sent Items 2097476 /living Home World U.S. Politics Crime Entertainment Health Tech Travel Living Business Sports Time.com Video iReport Impact Hot Topics » Surviving the Wedding Having It All Black in America Right on Your Money CNNU more topics »Weather Forecast International Editionupdated 10:17 a.m. EDT, Fri July 4, 2008 Share this on: Mixx Digg Facebook del.icio.us reddit StumbleUpon MySpace How much skin is too much at the office?Story Highlights Consider office dress code that's as specific as possible, say experts Horror stories include unshowered worker in sweats and baseball cap In another example, workers wore tank tops, exposed bra straps, flip-flops Other code factors: Resentment by co-workers, safety, branding, environment Next Article in Living » Read VIDEO NEW YORK (AP) -- Here's a scenario very likely to happen at a small business this summer: The owner arrives in the morning, and is greeted not only by the company's receptionist, but her exposed navel. And maybe her nose ring too. Employees showing up for work in tank tops or flip-flops may inspire the boss to write an office dress code. In the summer heat, many employees, particularly those in their first jobs, may show up for work in rather skimpy attire that a small business owner feels is unsuitable for the workplace. The solution is to create a dress code -- something that every business has the right to do. Tory Johnson dealt with the issue just a few weeks ago. Three interns, ages 19 to 21, showed up at Johnson's Manhattan recruitment services firm with tank tops, exposed bra straps and flip-flops. "Not only is that totally inappropriate in any office -- I couldn't care less how hot it is outside -- but since my company focuses on the advancement of professional women, it's doubly unacceptable to me," said Johnson, CEO of Women For Hire. Watch an expert on office dress codes » Johnson spoke to the young women, and "they got it immediately." As is often the case, they had no idea about how they should dress for work. Bonnie Beirne, director of service operations for Administaff Inc., a Houston-based company that provides human resources outsourcing, says a dress code should be in writing, but even if a business doesn't have one yet, an owner still has the right to tell a staffer that he or she needs to wear more appropriate attire. Don't Miss Too tattooed to work Reasons why you're not getting hired That means telling an employee: "I realize we don't have something in writing, but I'm going to be putting together a policy communicating our dress code policy more formally." An owner also needs to explain to workers that how they dress delivers a message to customers and vendors. "It goes back to image and branding for your company -- what are you saying to your customers," Beirne said. When staffers dress for work as if they're going to the beach, there's also likely to be plenty of resentment among co-workers who do dress more professionally. At Logos Research Systems Inc., the dress code was ultra-casual; even the president came in wearing shorts. Just about anything was OK -- until a new employee showed up not only in sweats and a baseball cap, but not having taken a shower for several days running. Dan Pritchett, vice president for marketing and business development for the Bellingham, Washington-based software company, said, "sadly, we were big chickens, we waited longer than we should have" to address the situation. But after about three weeks, it had to be dealt with and the staffer was told to dress better and take a shower. "The reaction was much rejoicing because the majority of the people couldn't take the smell and the look," Pritchett said. Logos does have a dress code now, but it's still quite lenient; shorts, but not cut-offs, are OK. But Pritchett said the general attire in the company, while casual, has become much more serious because the president, Pritchett's brother Bob, is dressing a little more professionally. "He got tired of being embarrassed" when customers, vendors, even journalists would show up wearing business clothes while the president was wearing shorts, Dan Pritchett said. When Bob started dressing better, wearing slacks and a button-down shirt, so did staffers. There are other issues beyond appearance that can make a dress code crucial, such as worker safety. Many manufacturing companies have dress codes to ensure that garments aren't caught in machinery, for example. Even in an office setting, safety can be an issue. If someone drops a box of computer paper and it lands on the foot of an employee wearing only flip-flops, that can lead to injury and a workers compensation case. A dress code should spell out what is and isn't appropriate for that company. But it should be specific: For example, if you want to allow workers to wear shorts, you should make clear how long they should be, and if you are banning cut-offs, say so. If it's all right for women to wear sleeveless tops but not tank tops, and if their blouses shouldn't be made of see-through fabric, you need to state that as well. When you do address the issue with an individual employee, Beirne suggests doing so in a non-threatening manner. Very often, a worker truly doesn't realize that his or her clothes don't belong in a workplace. And make it clear you're not singling out this employee -- you'll be creating a dress code for everyone to follow. "Keep explaining, this is how we want our company to be run," she said. With that context, employees aren't likely to balk, as Johnson and Pritchett's company found. If they do, then an owner is likely to end up dealing with a performance and discipline issue. You should also consider the physical environment in your company -- is there a lot of exposed skin in your office because the air conditioning is faulty, or because there are no shades on the windows to prevent the sun from streaming in? If so, you should remedy the situation, and, in the process, acknowledge your employees' needs. Even though we are both on the slender side, no one wants to see our 40+ year old butt cracks, especially at work...and we'd like to be spared the same! On the other end of the spectrum, there are stores that will dress us like mother earth in flowy, granola clothes that are also not work-appropriate in a business setting. I agree that there are those who push the limits of the dress code (please...no more flip flops or birekenstocks!), but it's just plain hard these days to find something nicely tailored for the office. less Alan updated Sat July 5, 2008I learned a simple principle: don't wear anything to work that you wouldn't wear to church. I grew up in a large share ...more Over the past ten years, we have seen a gradual decline in 'dress etiquette' to the point where I am convinced that most of the present generation have no idea what the word "proper" means. I grew up in a large sharecropping, southern family during the 40, 50s and 60s and even as broke as we were, we had our 'good clothes' for church and special occasions; school clothes that were neat, clean and pressed; and around the house clothes which were pretty much stuff you wouldn't want anyone outside of the family to see you in. Over the years, people of my generation has pretty much maintained that dress code. I think the source of all problems of our social decline is PARENTS. Too many families are run by harried parents --- and probably single parents who have neither the time or inclination to do much with their kids but feed and clothe them...I think they believe that is their full requirement as parents. Generational rejection of all that went before has brought us to the point where half naked, ill-dressed, uncouthed people show up at work, church, school and everywhere else looking like they were raised by Dopey, Trashy and Sleazy. We will have better dressed and more respectably behaved young people, when we get a generation of parents that place value on common decency...or even know what it is. I'm not for going back to wearing gloves everywhere (which women and girls did when I was growing up). But for God sakes, we don't need to see your underwear, --- and in some cases, the lack thereof. Also, when I was growing up, it was considered a major slam against your family for anyone to ask rhetorically: 'Who raised you to behave like that.' On behalf of an older generation tired of seeing those hideous tattoos that look like some kind of skin disease all over beautiful young bodies...who raised you to behave this way? less Rexx updated Fri July 4, 2008Its pretty simple. <table width="550" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="background-color:#ffffff;margin-bottom:10px;"> <tr> <td valign="top" style="padding:20px 0px 15px 2px;"> <a href="http://n.npr.org/NPRC/jN805630_3574.htm"><img src="http://media.npr.org/programs/watc/features/2008/july/marsalis_nelson_200.jpg" width="200" height="150" style="border:1px solid #000000;" alt="" /></a> </td> <td valign="top" style="font-family:arial;padding:20px 10px 10px 15px;"> <div style="text-transform:uppercase;color:#969696;margin:0;padding:0;font-size:10px;">Interviews & Profiles</div> <div style="font-weight:bold;margin-bottom:10px;padding:0;font-size:16px;"><a href="http://n.npr.org/NPRC/jN805630_3574.htm" style="color:#113e98;text-decoration:underline;">Wynton And Willie: Two Men Playing The Blues</a></div> <div style="line-height:15px;padding:0;font-size:12px;margin-bottom:10px;">Country music legend Willie Nelson and jazz trumpeter Wynton Marsalis discover common ground and a mutual love of jazz standards and the blues on their album <em>Two Men With The Blues</em>. The artists discuss their first ever collaboration. </div> </td> </tr> <tr><td colspan="2" style="height:3px;background-color:#c83030;"></td></tr> </table> <!-- other stories --> <table width="550" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="margin-bottom:10px;"> <tr> <td valign="top" style="padding:7px 10px 7px 2px;"> <a href="http://n.npr.org/NPRC/jN805630_3575.htm"><img src="http://media.npr.org/programs/atc/features/2008/july/1homemadejamz75.jpg" width="75" height="75" style="border:1px solid #000000;" alt="" /></a> </td> <td valign="top" style="padding:7px 0 7px 0;font-family:arial;"> <div style="text-transform:uppercase;color:#969696;margin:0;padding:0;font-size:10px;">Studio Sessions</div> <div style="font-weight:bold;margin:0 0 2px 0;padding:0;font-size:14px;"><a href="http://n.npr.org/NPRC/jN805630_3575.htm" style="color:#113e98;text-decoration:underline;">A Blues Family, Kicking Out Homemade Jamz</a></div> <div style="line-height:15px;padding:0;font-size:12px;">For the Perry siblings of Tupelo, Miss. -- ages 9, 14 and 16 -- making music involves making unique instruments from car parts. The young family band with astonishingly mature blues chops demonstrates its craft in NPR's Studio 4A.</div> <a href="http://n.npr.org/NPRC/jN805630_3575.htm" style="color:#113e98;text-decoration:none;font-weight:bold;font-size:12px;">Watch the Video &raquo;</a> </td> </tr> <tr><td colspan="2" style="height:10px;"><hr style="color:#d8d8d8;background-color:#d8d8d8;margin:0;padding:0;border:0;height:1px;" /></td></tr> <tr> <td valign="top" style="padding:7px 10px 7px 2px;"> <a href="http://n.npr.org/NPRC/jN805630_3576.htm"><img src="http://media.npr.org/music/liveconcerts/2008/fleetfoxes/live75.jpg" width="75" height="75" style="border:1px solid #000000;" alt="" /></a> </td> <td valign="top" style="padding:7px 0 7px 0;font-family:arial;"> <div style="text-transform:uppercase;color:#969696;margin:0;padding:0;font-size:10px;">Live Concerts</div> <div style="font-weight:bold;margin:0 0 2px 0;padding:0;font-size:14px;"><a href="http://n.npr.org/NPRC/jN805630_3576.htm" style="color:#113e98;text-decoration:underline;">Fleet Foxes: Stunning and Humble</a></div> <div style="line-height:15px;padding:0;font-size:12px;">Fleet Foxes is one of the year's breakout acts. The group's self-titled debut, released earlier this year on the Sub Pop label, has earned universal acclaim for its timeless mix of folk, choral and rock. Hear the majestic Fleet Foxes recorded live in concert from Washington, D.C.'s Black Cat.</div> <a href="http://n.npr.org/NPRC/jN805630_3576.htm" style="color:#113e98;text-decoration:none;font-weight:bold;font-size:12px;">Hear the Concert &raquo;</a> </td> </tr> <tr><td colspan="2" style="height:10px;"><hr style="color:#d8d8d8;background-color:#d8d8d8;margin:0;padding:0;border:0;height:1px;" /></td></tr> <tr> <td valign="top" style="padding:7px 10px 7px 2px;"> <a href="http://n.npr.org/NPRC/jN805630_3577.htm"><img src="http://media.npr.org/programs/wc/images/2008/07/goldfrapp75.jpg" width="75" height="75" style="border:1px solid #000000;" alt="" /></a> </td> <td valign="top" style="padding:7px 0 7px 0;font-family:arial;"> <div style="text-transform:uppercase;color:#969696;margin:0;padding:0;font-size:10px;">World Cafe</div> <div style="font-weight:bold;margin:0 0 2px 0;padding:0;font-size:14px;"><a href="http://n.npr.org/NPRC/jN805630_3577.htm" style="color:#113e98;text-decoration:underline;">Goldfrapp: The Lillywhite Session</a></div> <div style="line-height:15px;padding:0;font-size:12px;">Once an electronic duo, Goldfrapp now embraces dance, glam-rock, and folk on Seventh Tree. British super-diva Allison Goldfrapp and her collaborator, Will Gregory, perform music from the new album with the legendary Steve Lillywhite at the production board. </div> </td> </tr> <tr><td colspan="2" style="height:10px;"><hr style="color:#d8d8d8;background-color:#d8d8d8;margin:0;padding:0;border:0;height:1px;" /></td></tr> <tr> <td valign="top" style="padding:7px 10px 7px 2px;"> <a href="http://n.npr.org/NPRC/jN805630_3578.htm"><img src="http://media.npr.org/music/mountain/2008/july/farkatoure75.jpg" width="75" height="75" style="border:1px solid #000000;" alt="" /></a> </td> <td valign="top" style="padding:7px 0 7px 0;font-family:arial;"> <div style="text-transform:uppercase;color:#969696;margin:0;padding:0;font-size:10px;">Mountain Stage</div> <div style="font-weight:bold;margin:0 0 2px 0;padding:0;font-size:14px;"><a href="http://n.npr.org/NPRC/jN805630_3578.htm" style="color:#113e98;text-decoration:underline;">Vieux Farka Toure: Of Bamako And Banjos</a></div> <div style="line-height:15px;padding:0;font-size:12px;">The son of great Malian bluesman Ali Farka Toure performs with Mama Sissoko on ngoni, a West African ancestor of the banjo. The show is part of our new concert series from West Virginia's popular Mountain Stage.</div> </td> </tr> <tr><td colspan="2" style="height:10px;"><hr style="color:#d8d8d8;background-color: #d8d8d8;margin:0;padding:0;border:0;height:1px;" /></td></tr> <tr> <td valign="top" style="padding:7px 10px 7px 2px;"> <a href="http://n.npr.org/NPRC/jN805630_3579.htm"><img src="http://media.npr.org/music/images/2008/classical_lists/grandcanyon75.jpg" width="75" height="75" style="border:1px solid #000000;" alt="" / ></a> </td> <td valign="top" style="padding:7px 0 7px 0;font-family:arial;"> <div style="text-transform:uppercase;color:#969696;margin:0;padding:0;font-size:10px;">Music Lists</div> <div style="font-weight:bold;margin:0 0 2px 0;padding:0;font-size:14px;"><a href="http://n.npr.org/NPRC/jN805630_3579.htm" style="color:#113e98;text-decoration:underline;">Classical Road Trip: Musical Milestones</a></div> <div style="line-height:15px;padding:0;font-size:12px;">Tired of paying too much for gas? Take a virtual road trip with some of America's greatest composers. Stops include Leonard Bernstein's New York and Charles Ives' New England, Ferde Grofe's Grand Canyon and Virgil Thomson's Great Plains. </div> <a href="http://n.npr.org/NPRC/jN805630_3579.htm" style="color:#113e98;text-decoration:none;font-weight:bold;font-size:12px;">Hear the Music &raquo;</a> </td> </tr> </table> <!-- promos --> <table width="550" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="border-top:1px solid #d8d8d8;background-color:#e4e9f0;"> <tr> <td valign="top" style="padding:15px 0 20px 40px;"> <table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="width:220px;"> <tr> <td colspan="2" style="font-size:11px;font-family:arial;padding-bottom:3px;font-weight:bold;">NPR Books</td> </tr> <tr> <td valign="top" style="padding-right:5px;width:40px;"><a href="http://n.npr.org/NPRC/jN805630_3580.htm"><img src="http://media.npr.org/email/booknotes/images/summer40.jpg" width="40" height="40" border="0" alt="Promo" /></a></td> <td style="font-size:11px;font-family:arial;"><div><a href="http://n.npr.org/NPRC/jN805630_3580.htm" style="color:#c83030;font-weight:bold;text-decoration:none;">Summer Reading</a></div>Critics' picks and must reads for the avid summer reader.</td> </tr> </table> </td> <td valign="top" style="padding:15px 40px 20px 30px;"> <table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="width:220px;"> <tr> <td colspan="2" style="font-size:11px;font-family:arial;padding-bottom:3px;font-weight:bold;">NPR Music</td> </tr> <tr> <td valign="top" style="padding-right:5px;"><a href="http://n.npr.org/NPRC/jN805630_3581.htm"><img src="http://media.npr.org/email/booknotes/images/secondstage40.jpg" width="40" height="40" border="0" alt="Promo" /></a></td> <td style="font-size:11px;font-family:arial;"><div><a href="http://n.npr.org/NPRC/jN805630_3581.htm" style="color:#c83030;font-weight:bold;text-decoration:none;">Second Stage</a></div>Every weekday, discover the best in new, breakout and unsigned artists. Is it too little, too late to win over black voters? </div> </td> </tr> <tr><td colspan="2" style="height:3px;background-color:#c83030;"></td></tr> </table> <!-- other stories --> <table width="550" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="margin-bottom:10px;"> <tr> <td valign="top" style="padding:7px 20px 7px 40px;font-family:arial;"> <div style="text-transform:uppercase;color:#969696;margin:0;padding:0;font-size:10px;">Nation</div> <div style="font-weight:bold;margin:0 0 2px 0;padding:0;font-size:14px;"><a href="http://n.npr.org/NPRC/jN912610_3997.htm"" style="color:#113e98;text-decoration:underline;">Assessing the Future of the NAACP</a></div> <div style="line-height:15px;padding:0;font-size:12px;">The NAACP was formed nearly a century ago, working tirelessly to end lynching and break down economic and judicial barriers. Joining in are Ron Sturm, owner of the Iridium Jazz Club; musician Dennis Winslett; and Peter Williams, artistic director of Yoshi's Jazz Club.</div> </td> </tr> <tr><td style="height:10px;"><hr style="color:#d8d8d8;background-color:#d8d8d8;margin:0;padding:0;border:0;height:1px;" /></td></tr> <tr> <td valign="top" style="padding:7px 20px 7px 40px;font-family:arial;"> <div style="text-transform:uppercase;color:#969696;margin:0;padding:0;font-size:10px;">Sports</div> <div style="font-weight:bold;margin:0 0 2px 0;padding:0;font-size:14px;"><a href="http://n.npr.org/NPRC/jN912610_3999.htm" style="color:#113e98;text-decoration:underline;">Sports Round-Up: NFL Targets Gang Hand Signs</a></div> <div style="line-height:15px;padding:0;font-size:12px;">NPR's Tony Cox welcomes sports bloggers Kevin Figgers and Carron Phillips to give their perspectives on the biggest sports stories of the day. Barlow opens his mouth to sing, Sebadoh's 1993 single "Soul and Fire" has already conveyed a knotty bundle of conflicting emotions: They're all there in the aching, deliberately paced opening notes. From there, Barlow catalogs a relationship's combustible ingredients before announcing, "I think our love is coming to an end."</div> <div style="padding:3px 0 0 3px;"><a href="http://n.npr.org/NPRC/jN821714_3608.htm"><img src="http://media.npr.org/email/songoftheday/images/listenmain.gif" width="124" height="29" border="0" alt="Listen" /></a></div> </td> </tr> <tr><td colspan="2"><div style="font-family:arial;font-size:12px;color:#444444;margin-bottom:20px;">Song: "Soul and Fire" | Artist: Sebadoh | CD: <em>Bubble and Scrape</em> | Genre: Indie-Rock</div></td></tr> <tr><td colspan="2" style="height:3px;background-color:#c83030;"></td></tr> </table> <!-- previous sotd --> <table width="550" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0"> <tr> <td valign="top" style="font-size:12px;font-family:arial;padding:10px 10px 0 0;width:250px;"> <div style="font-size:14px;color:#444444;font-weight:bold;margin-bottom:10px;">Previous Song of the Day</div> <div style="font-size:12px;color:#444444;margin-bottom:5px;">Song: "Nike Boots" | Artist: Wale</div> <div style="font-size:12px;color:#444444;margin-bottom:5px;">CD: MP3 Only</div> <div style="font-size:12px;color:#444444;margin-bottom:5px;">Genre: Hip-Hop</div> <div style="padding:3px 0 0 3px;"><a href="http://n.npr.org/NPRC/jN821714_3609.htm"><img src="http://media.npr.org/email/songoftheday/images/listensub.gif" width="121" height="14" border="0" alt="Listen" /></a></div> </td> <td valign="top" style="font-family:arial;padding-top:10px;padding-right:5px;font-size:13px;width:255px;"> <div style="font-weight:bold;margin-bottom:2px;"><a href="http://n.npr.org/NPRC/jN821714_3609.htm" style="color:#113e98;text-decoration:underline;">Wale: Flyer Than The Rest Of 'Em</a></div> <div style="padding-bottom:20px;">After releasing a popular mix tape last year, D.C. rapper Wale signed a major-label deal. A look at a young star whose fleeting fame can't mask her gnawing sadness, the song practically begs to be picked apart, its narrator psychoanalyzed for good measure.</div> </td> </tr> </table> <!-- more links --> <table width="550" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0"> <tr> <td colspan="2" style="font-family:arial;text-transform:uppercase;font-weight:bold;background-color:#f57109;text-transform:uppercase;font-size:12px;padding:4px 6px;"><a href="http://n.npr.org/NPRC/jN885719_3872.htm" style="text-decoration:none;color:#fff;">More at NPR.org</a></td> </tr> <tr> <td valign="top" style="font-size:12px;font-family:arial;padding:10px 10px 0 0;width:250px;margin:0;"> <ul style="list-style-type:square;color:#f57109;line-height:17px;margin:0 0 15px 12px;padding:0 0 0 12px;"> <li><a href="http://n.npr.org/NPRC/jN885719_3876.htm" style="color:#f57109;text-decoration:none;">In Performance: Live Concerts from NPR</a></li> <li><a href="http://n.npr.org/NPRC/jN885719_3877.htm" style="color:#f57109;text-decoration:none;">All Songs Considered</a></li> <li><a href="http://n.npr.org/NPRC/jN885719_3878.htm" style="color:#f57109;text-decoration:none;">World Café</a></li> <li><a href="http://n.npr.org/NPRC/jN885719_3879.htm" style="color:#f57109;text-decoration:none;">Video Sessions</a></li> <li><a href="http://n.npr.org/NPRC/jN885719_3880.htm" style="color:#f57109;text-decoration:none;">Music Lists</a></li> </ul> </td> <td valign="top" style="font-family:arial;padding-top:10px;padding-right:5px;font-size:12px;width:255px;"> <div style="font-weight:bold;margin-bottom:2px;"><a href="http://n.npr.org/NPRC/jN885719_3881.htm" style="color:#f57109;text-decoration:none;">More "Song of the Day" &raquo;</a></div> <div style="padding-bottom:20px;">Every weekday, "Song of the Day" highlights another new or notable song with a short essay and a chance to hear the music itself.
